  "stage": {
    "id": "decision_frameworks",
    "stageNumber": 2,
    "title": "DAO Decision-Making Frameworks",
    "roomWidth": 20,
    "roomHeight": 15,
    "concepts": [
      {
        "id": "convex_concave_decisions",
        "title": "Convex vs Concave Decision-Making",
        "content": "## Key Question: Where is the Best Choice?\n\nVitalik Buterin categorized decision-making into **Convex** and **Concave** in his 2022 essay.\n\n### Convex Situation — \"Being in the middle is the worst\"\n\nSituations where choosing definitively between A or B produces better results.\n\n**Military strategy example**: Splitting forces in half to attack two directions results in insufficient power in both places, losing everywhere. Concentrating on one direction is better.\n\n**Product launch example**: Must decide between February or March launch. \"Half in February, half in March\" is impossible.\n\n→ **Fast solo decision-makers (CEO, leaders)** are advantageous\n\n### Concave Situation — \"Spreading it around is better\"\n\nSituations where the middle value produces better results than extreme choices.\n\n**Research fund example**: Distributing $2M research funds as $1M each to two promising projects has higher success probability than giving $2M to one project.\n\n**Policy example**: A compromise reflecting diverse opinions has fewer side effects than extreme single policies.\n\n→ **Decentralized voting reflecting multiple opinions** is advantageous\n\n## Vitalik's Key Argument\n\n> DAO's decentralized decision-making isn't good for all situations—it should only be used when **the problem is Concave**.\n\nCentralized few handle Convex problems, entire community decides Concave problems—a **hybrid structure** is realistic.",
        "position": {
          "x": 5,
          "y": 6
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "dao_vs_corporation",
        "title": "DAO vs Corporation Debate",
        "content": "## The Corporation Camp's Argument\n\nCriticism spread that \"Token + Voting structure DAOs don't work,\" along with predictions that \"DAOs will eventually converge to corporate structures.\"\n\n**Key arguments**:\n- Hierarchy makes decision-making efficient\n- Governance principles verified over centuries exist\n- DAOs cannot escape this\n\n## Vitalik's Counter-Argument: DAOs are Sovereigns\n\nAmerican philosopher **Curtis Yarvin** distinguished organizations into primary organizations (Sovereign) and secondary organizations (Contractual/Corporation).\n\n- **Corporation**: Strong external tools (law, enforcement) reduce failure probability\n- **Sovereign**: Risk of incentive structure being attacked or collapsing without external support\n\n> \"DAOs have no 'Sovereign' above them and often perform sovereign functions (currency, arbitration). Therefore, DAOs should learn more from **political science, not corporate management**.\"\n\n## Succession Problem\n\nThe biggest problem for Sovereigns, named by Samo Burja:\n\n> The lack of methods for systems to continuously transition to the next group when founding groups leave\n\nBitcoin works even after Satoshi disappeared. But most DAOs haven't yet proven sustainable structures without core teams.",
        "position": {
          "x": 9,
          "y": 6
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "pod_structure",
        "title": "Pod Structure and Hybrid Governance",
        "content": "## Ukraine DAO Case\n\nAs a counter-example to the notion that DAOs must be \"entirely decentralized,\" there's the **Ukraine DAO's Pod structure**.\n\n### What is Pod Structure?\n\n- **Fundraising**: Decentralized approach (entire community decides)\n- **Fund execution**: **Centralized** task execution within Pods after allocation\n\nLike company departments, Pods operate independently within allocated resources.\n\n## Criteria for Evaluating DAO Decentralization\n\nTwo criteria for evaluating whether a well-built DAO is meaningfully decentralized:\n\n### 1. Pod Autonomy\n\nReceive resources from Core, but make independent decisions otherwise. If Core intervenes in every Pod decision, it's not true decentralization.\n\n### 2. Decentralization and Diversity of Core Governance\n\nDoesn't have to be governance tokens, but needs broader, more diverse participants. If a few whales dictate all decisions, it's no different from centralization.\n\n## Ideal Composition\n\n> The upper level (Core) should focus on **Concave situations**, and the lower level (Pod) should focus on **Convex situations**.\n\n- Core: Fund allocation, long-term direction (Concave) → Decentralized voting\n- Pod: Specific execution, quick decisions (Convex) → Few leaders decide",
        "position": {
          "x": 13,
          "y": 6
        },
        "type": "text"
      }
    ],
    "quizzes": [
      {
        "id": "quiz-stage-2-lesson-0-0",
        "question": "What type is a decision to allocate public goods funding across multiple projects?",
        "type": "multiple-choice",
        "options": [
          "Convex — Best to concentrate resources on the single highest-impact project",
          "Concave — Best to distribute across multiple projects",
          "Linear — Outcome is proportional to funding amount regardless of distribution",
          "Convex — Best to let a single expert committee pick the optimal allocation"
        ],
        "correctAnswer": "Concave — Best to distribute across multiple projects",
        "position": {
